title: For Trade:  Dan Wesson .357 Magnum 4 inch barrel 6 shot revolver
postcontent:
The gun in the pic is a Dan Wesson (model 15-2) 6 shot in 357 Magnum from the first Dan Wesson company at Monson, MA. This one was made in the late 70's, putting it at 30+ years old. It sat in a gun safe for a long time.

The cool thing about Dan Wessons is that the barrels are easily removed and installed with a special tool. The barrels are threaded on both ends. One end screws into the frame and you use a .006 feeler gauge to set the gap between the barrel and the cylinder. Then you slide the accompanying shroud over the barrel and tighten it down with the barrel nut. This applies tension on both ends of the barrel reducing harmonic vibrations and improving accuracy. Dan Wesson made barrels from 2 ½ to 15 inches!

Yours for $530.

Second is a Shooters Arms Manufacturing (SAM) M1911 Military.  Full size 1911 with one 8-round magazine, one 7-round Colt factory magazine (not pictured), WRB XMH holster with thumb break and magazine pouch (not pictured), zippered locking soft case, rubber Hogue grips with finger grooves, wood Hogue Sig Sauer grips, 8 brand new 16 lb recoil springs, a .45 caliber cleaning kit, 20 rounds of Federal Premium low recoil Hydra Shok ammo, and an antique leather shoulder holster with built-in spring retention.  
I've put exactly 132 rounds through the pistol.  There's a little surface rust in the grip screw head slots from swapping grips. and the gun was dropped so there's a ding on the front left side of the slide, and the left corner of the hammer and safety (doesn't affect function).  The guy I bought the leather shoulder holster from told me it's from WWII, but there's no markings.  It's in pretty rough shape.
